
Chapter 1 — The Machine Learning Landscape (Summary)

(English, structured, with figure placements)

1. What Is Machine Learning?

Machine Learning (ML) is defined as the science and art of programming computers to learn from data.
Arthur Samuel (1959) describes ML as the field that gives computers the ability to learn without being explicitly programmed.
Tom Mitchell (1997) provides an operational definition:
A program learns from experience (E) on task (T) with performance metric (P) if its performance on T improves with E.

A spam filter is a practical example:

Task (T): classify emails as spam or ham

Experience (E): past labeled emails

Performance (P): accuracy

Downloading data (e.g., Wikipedia) is not ML unless performance on a task improves.

2. Why Use Machine Learning?
Traditional Rule-Based Programming

Writing a spam filter manually requires crafting many rules such as detecting specific words (“4U”, “credit card”, “free”).
This results in long, fragile, and hard-to-maintain code.

Insert Figure 1-1 — Traditional approach
![Figure 1-1: Traditional rule-based approach](../images/ch1/figure1-1.png)
(Figure shows a manual rule-writing process: study problem → write rules → test → launch.)

ML-Based Approach

A Machine Learning spam filter automatically learns which words/phrases are predictive of spam by analyzing patterns in labeled emails.

Insert Figure 1-2 — ML approach
![Figure 1-2: The Machine Learning approach](../images/ch1/figure1-2.png)
(Figure shows: provide data → train ML algorithm → evaluate → launch.)

ML is easier to update, more scalable, and more adaptive.

Automatic Adaptation to New Patterns

If spammers modify wording (“4U” → “For U”), rule-based programs must be manually updated.
ML systems adapt automatically by learning from new examples.

Insert Figure 1-3 — Automatic adaptation
![Figure 1-3: Automatically adapting to change](../images/ch1/figure1-3.png)
(Figure shows the system updating itself when new spam patterns emerge.)

ML for Complex or Unsolvable Problems

Some tasks—like large-vocabulary speech recognition—are too complex for hand-crafted rules.
ML is also used for discovering patterns in data (data mining).

ML Helps Humans Learn

By analyzing models (e.g., spam classifier weights), humans can discover correlations and insights.

Insert Figure 1-4 — ML helping humans learn
![Figure 1-4: Machine Learning can help humans learn](../images/ch1/figure1-4.png)

3. Summary of ML Benefits

ML excels when:

Manual rules are too complex or numerous

No known algorithm exists

Environments change frequently

Insights need to be extracted from large datasets

4. Examples of Machine Learning Applications

The chapter lists many ML tasks and typical algorithms for each (only key highlights):

Application	ML Technique
Image product classification	CNNs
Tumor detection (semantic segmentation)	CNNs
News article classification	RNNs, CNNs, Transformers
Offensive text detection	NLP classification
Document summarization	Sequence-to-sequence NLP
Chatbots	NLP + NLU modules
Revenue forecasting	Regression models
Voice command apps	Speech recognition (RNNs, CNNs, Transformers)
Fraud detection	Anomaly detection
Customer segmentation	Clustering
Dimensionality visualization	PCA, t-SNE
Recommender systems	Neural networks
Game-playing bots	Reinforcement Learning
5. Types of Machine Learning Systems

ML systems are categorized by:

A. Supervision Level

Supervised Learning: training data includes labels

Classification (e.g., spam detection)

Regression (predict numeric values)

